{"key":"processedPost-13134399","value":{"id":13134399,"first":13133566,"last":13149478,"when":1283377154,"utime":"09/02/10 12:39 AM","content":"If there's only one hole in the bottom, it's serving as a two way street.&nbsp; You're not pulling a vacuum in the container because of CO2 'draining out'.&nbsp; The reason we don't only use one hole in a terrarium is because fresh air is the number one pinning trigger.&nbsp; If we could maintain humidity in open air, that would be the best of all, and it isn't just about CO2.&nbsp; It's about causing evaporation of moisture from the substrate.<br />We've all seen the demonstration of CO2 in a glass and how you can pour it on a candle and put the flame out.&nbsp; That's not the principle at work in a mushroom terrarium, or especially in a larger farm such as mine shown below, which is underground and has no 'drainage' provisions at the bottom for release of gasses.&nbsp; Both vents are on the ceiling, and pass upwards 20' to the surface.&nbsp; The results speak for themselves.&nbsp; CO2 levels run around 500ppm to 600ppm during full production, and they're no higher on the bottom shelves than on the top ones.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/10-30/054482710-Mountain_Mushroom_Farm-Shiitake.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/10-30/054482710-thumb_Mountain_Mushroom_Farm-Shiitake.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: Oven sterilized TC, Molecular weight fruiting chamber"}}